The paper proposes a new architecture for generative adversarial networks that is specifically designed for image generation, particularly of natural scenes. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of convolutional and de-convolutional layers, which are commonly used in deep learning for image processing. This further supports the likelihood of the paper belonging to the cs.CV sub-category. 

The paper also discusses the use of architectures based on fully convolutional networks, which are commonly used in deep learning for tasks such as semantic segmentation and object detection. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

Furthermore, the paper discusses the generation of natural textures such as geologic structures, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper discusses the use of dilated layers, which are commonly used in deep learning for tasks such as image segmentation and object detection. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Overall, the most likely sub-categories for this paper are cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.GR, and cs.NE, in that order.
